const INDUSTRY_NOTES = {
  'Construction / General Contractor': 'For contractors, job costing is everything. Use Classes or Projects in QBO to track profitability per job. Subcontractor payments over $600/year require 1099-NEC. Retainage held by customers stays in A/R until released — separate it out for clearer aging.',
  'E-commerce (Amazon / Shopify / Etsy)': 'Always record gross sales separately from platform fees — never net them. Amazon settlements include sales, refunds, fees, and reserves bundled together; use A2X or a journal entry to break them out. Track inventory by location for FBA accuracy.',
  'Real Estate Investor / Rental': 'Use Classes (or one QBO company file per property if portfolios are large) to track each property separately. Capitalize improvements over $2,500 to a fixed asset; expense smaller repairs. Security deposits are a liability, not income.',
  'Restaurant / Food Service': 'Daily Sales Summary journal entries beat individual transactions. Track food cost % (target 28-35%) and labor cost % (target 25-35%) religiously. Third-party delivery should be booked at gross with commission as COGS to show true revenue.',
  'Trucking / Transportation': 'Per-truck profitability requires Classes or Locations in QBO. Track fuel by truck via fuel cards. Owner-operator settlements differ from W-2 driver wages — keep them in separate COGS accounts. Don\'t forget IFTA quarterly filings.',
  'Law Firm / Professional Services': 'IOLTA trust accounts MUST reconcile to the penny — three-way reconciliation (bank, client ledger, trust liability) is required by every state bar. Advanced client costs are an asset until billed back to the client.',
  'SaaS / Tech Startup': 'Recognize subscription revenue ratably over the service period — annual plans go to deferred revenue first. Track ARR/MRR outside QBO and reconcile monthly. Capitalize commissions under ASC 606 if material.',
  'Real Estate Agent / Realtor': 'Track commissions at gross with broker splits as COGS to see your true production. Most agents are 1099 contractors of their brokerage — Schedule C ready. Lead generation costs are a major write-off.',
  'Medical / Dental Practice': 'Insurance contractual adjustments are not bad debt — they are contra-revenue. Track production vs collections separately. HSA and FSA payments often arrive weeks late; reconcile patient balances monthly.',
  'Nonprofit / 501(c)(3)': 'Restricted vs unrestricted net assets matter for Form 990. Track grants by funder using Classes. Functional expense allocation (Program / M&G / Fundraising) is required for the 990 — set up reporting early.',
  'Property Management': 'Trust accounting is non-negotiable. Each owner\'s funds must be tracked separately and reconcile to the trust bank balance. Management fees are your income; rent collected is a liability until paid to owners.',
  'Auto Repair Shop': 'Track labor hours sold vs hours paid for efficiency. Parts markup is your margin engine — keep parts cost and parts sales in separate accounts. Sublet work (alignment, machine shop) is COGS, not expense.',
  'Salon / Spa / Beauty': 'Tips are a pass-through liability — never income to the salon. Gift card sales are liabilities until redeemed. Booth renters are 1099 contractors; commission stylists are employees — classification matters for payroll.',
  'Retail Store': 'Inventory must be reconciled to physical counts at least annually. Sales tax payable is a liability, not income — set up automated sales tax in QBO. Track shrinkage as a separate COGS line for visibility.',
  'Consulting / Coaching': 'Retainers received in advance are deferred revenue, not income, until earned. Track utilization (billable hours / total hours) outside QBO. Course income may have refund periods — consider a refund reserve.',
  'Marketing / Creative Agency': 'Bill ad spend at gross with the cost as pass-through COGS, or at net (just your management fee) — pick one and be consistent. Unbilled WIP at month-end should be accrued for accurate revenue recognition.',
  'Accounting / Tax / CFO Firm (Scaling with Remote Bookkeepers)': 'The capacity ceiling is the partner. Firms break through $500K+ revenue only when they shift from "partner does the work" to "partner reviews work done by Tier 1 (offshore bookkeepers) and Tier 2 (senior reviewers)." Goal mix: 60% Tier 1 production, 25% Tier 2 review, 15% partner advisory. Offshore bookkeepers are SUBCONTRACTOR COSTS in COGS (not wages) — W-8 BEN on file, paid via Deel/Remote/Wise. Track clients-per-bookkeeper ratio (target 18-25 monthly clients per experienced offshore bookkeeper), realization rate (90%+ retainer / 80%+ tax / 70%+ cleanup), and utilization rate (65-75% senior staff, 50-60% partners). Separate Monthly Recurring Revenue (bookkeeping, CFO retainers) from project revenue (tax prep, audit, cleanup) — MRR drives firm valuation 5-8× vs 1× project. Practice management software (Karbon, Jetpack, Canopy, Financial Cents) is non-negotiable past 30 clients. Documented SOPs reduce new-hire ramp from 3 months to 2 weeks.',
};

